sections.heading: Overview
sections.content: This section lists the React components that are available to MDX files in the src/docs directory (or the docsPath defined in the theme options) of your Chicago Docs site. It also lists the available hooks that can be used in custom components to fetch data about your docs.

sections.heading: Overview
sections.content: All components described on this page are available automatically to all MDX files. There is no need to import them into your MDX files before using them.

sections.heading: Chicago Docs Components
sections.content: Chicago Docs comes with several components that help make it quick and easy for your users to find information on your product or API. Features such as site search and sidebar navigation mean your users won't get frustrated trying to find what they need. This section provides usage examples and a list of props accepted by each component.

sections.content: The Reqres API is a REST API with consistent resource-oriented URLs. Its purpose is to provide sample data for testing, prototyping, and even writing fake API documentation like this.

This API uses standard HTTP methods (or verbs): GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, and DELETE. It is CORS-enabled, accepts JSON-encoded request data (content type application/json), and returns JSON-encoded responses.
This API has two resources:
Access to this API is free and available 24/7. Reqres does not store request data.

sections.heading: The User Resource
sections.content: The User resource represents a fake user with attributes such as first_name and email. Use this resource when you need sample user data for a project.

sections.heading: The User Resource
sections.content: To retrieve a specific user, make a GET request to this endpoint and provide the user's id.

sections.heading: The User Resource
sections.content: To retrieve a list of users, make a GET request to this endpoint. Optionally provide the page number and/or the number of users per page. The total number of users available is 12.

sections.heading: The User Resource
sections.content: To create a new user, make a POST request to this endpoint with any JSON data you want.

sections.heading: The User Resource
sections.content: To update the data for an existing user, make a PUT or PATCH request to this endpoint with any data you want. Provide the id of the user to be updated.

sections.heading: The User Resource
sections.content: To delete an existing user, make a DELETE request to this endpoint. Provide the id of the user to be deleted.

sections.heading: The Color Resource
sections.content: The Color resource represents a Pantone Color of the Year, with attributes such as name and pantone_value. This resource is returned when any endpoint or data is sent to this API other than the User endpoints. This is useful for testing or demonstrating the front end of your project or a prototype without needing to set up your own API.

sections.heading: The Color Resource
sections.content: To retrieve a specific color, make a GET request to this endpoint (replace 'anything' with any value) and provide the color's id.

sections.heading: The Color Resource
sections.content: To retrieve a list of colors, make a GET request to this endpoint (replace 'anything' with any value). Optionally provide the page number and/or the number of colors per page. The total number of colors available is 12.

sections.heading: Overview
sections.content: The libraries used to style Chicago Docs components were chosen to make the site easy to customize for the largest number of users. You can re-style components using plain CSS or SASS. You can also style and customize components directly using Theme-UI or JavaScript.

sections.heading: Overview
sections.content: Customizing, altering, or replacing the styles and components of a Gatsby theme is called shadowing. Shadowing a theme file means creating a file with the same name in your site directory that will override the one from the theme.

sections.heading: Overview
sections.content: The new file you create should live in your site's src folder, in a directory with the same name as the theme you're shadowing. For example, to shadow the Chicago Docs Alert component, which has a file path of @kabartolo/gatsby-theme-chicago-docs/src/components/Alert/index.js, create the following folder structure in your site:

sections.heading: Overview
sections.content: If the file path in the original theme is theme-name/src/components/Alert/index.js, the shadowed file path should be your-site/src/theme-name/components/Alert/index.js.

sections.heading: Component Example
sections.content: The Alert component creates a colored box around the text you provide it. In the live preview below, try deleting variant="error". With no variant specified, the Alert component will use the default color variant information, which is blue.

sections.heading: Component Example
sections.content: What if you wanted to use the error variant as the default color instead? This example will show you how to shadow the Alert component and change its default color variant.

sections.heading: CSS
sections.content: Most styles in this theme are defined using SASS in CSS modules. Chicago Docs has also added regular class names to components. While this section describes how to shadow CSS module files, you can instead create a CSS file for your site and override the styles by selecting these class names. See Global styles below.

sections.heading: CSS
sections.content: Most components in this theme have a corresponding CSS module, and there is also a global SASS file where the SASS variables are defined.

sections.heading: CSS
sections.content: In Chicago Docs, each module is imported into the React component as a styles object containing the class names for the module:

sections.heading: CSS
sections.content: These class names are written in camel case in the styles object, such as styles.listItem or styles.leftColumn. However, in the CSS file, they are written in hyphenated lowercase. For example, styles.listItem should be referenced as .list-item in the CSS module file:

sections.content: Note that the 'list-item' class from the List module will be called something like this in the browser: list-module--list-item-KDSJ4 (where the string of characters at the end is random).

sections.content: If you need to make several style changes throughout the site, you can create a stylesheet and import it into a shadowed Layout component. The Layout component handles the global styles for the site. See Standard Styling with Global CSS files for guidance.

sections.heading: CSS

sections.content: Be sure to reference the regular CSS class names, not the CSS-module class names. For example, in header-container header-module--container---fnWC, the regular class name that can be selected is header-container. The other class name is generated by the CSS module and can change between renderings.

sections.heading: Theme-UI
sections.content: While most CSS styles are defined in CSS modules, any reusable site colors, borders, fonts, and other decorative styles are defined in a Theme-UI object using JavaScript syntax. These are the styles that form a consistent look and feel for your site and are used to display MDX. Theme-UI also takes care of the dark and light color themes for the site.

sections.heading: Theme-UI
sections.content: The Theme-UI files for Chicago Docs can be shadowed like any other file. Refer to the Chicago Docs Theme-UI Reference object to get the key for the style you want to shadow. Customizing, altering, or replacing the styles and components of a Gatsby theme is called shadowing. Shadowing a theme file means creating a file with the same name in your site directory that will override the one from the theme.

The new file you create should live in your site's src folder, in a directory with the same name as the theme you're shadowing.
